Following the discovery in 1964 of 9-tetrahydrocannabinol (THC) as the active molecule of the herbaceous plant 

Cannabis sativa
L. (Cannabaceae)

(

), research has continued to understand this plant with surprising effects, at times psychotropic, but with an increasing number of studies demonstrating a significant therapeutic potential (

). Despite a large number of synonyms 

C. sativa

is now considered the sole species of the 
Cannabis
genus but is divided into several phenotypes known as sub-species and varieties (

). 

C. sativa

has a wide range of chemical compounds, including cannabinoids, terpenoids, and flavonoids. All of these compounds are found in the fatty resin that develops in the trichomes of female plants (

). 

C. sativa

contains about 100 cannabinoids, including the most well-known THC, cannabidiol (CBD), cannabinol (CBN), cannabichromene (CBC), cannabig´erol (CBG), cannabinodiol (CBND), cannabielsoin (CBE), cannabicyclol (CBL), and cannabitriol (CBT) (

). In spite of having a common molecular framework (the C21 terpenophenolic skeleton), these compounds with widely varying chemical structures exhibit a wide range of different characteristics. THC is the most potent psychoactive compound, whereas CBD has no psychoactive effects but does have anti-inflammatory properties (

). The activities of phytocannabinoids with no psychotropic effects are now being researched since they are potentially therapeutic molecules (

; 

). Several cannabinoid-derived medications have already been approved, including DRONABINOL, a THC-synthesized drug used in the prevention or treatment of nausea and vomiting caused by chemotherapy, EPIDYOLEX, a CBD synthesized drug recently approved for the treatment of epilepsy crises, and SATIVEX, a 

C. sativa

extract containing THC and CBD with defined concentrations developed for the treatment of plaque sclerosis (

).

Phytocannabinoids, being phenolic compounds, should have the ability to inhibit harmful free radicals. Although these chemicals have been studied for their antioxidant potential (

; 

), very little is known about them. So far, the only noticeable effects of CBD as an antioxidant have been sufficiently demonstrated (

; 

). It was reported that CBD can decrease oxidative stress in two ways: by directly influencing the activity of oxidants and antioxidants, or by acting as an indirect inhibitor of molecular targets implicated in the redox system (Casares et al., 2020; 

; 

; 

). CBD has also been examined for its radical scavenging action, which has been found to be comparable to that of α- tocopherol (

). A recent study examined the antioxidant properties of seven phytocannabinoids including CBG, CBD, Δ9-THC, CBN, CBGA, CBDA, and Δ9-THCA using spectrophotometric methods such as ABTS, DPPH, ORAC, CUPRAC, beta-carotene, and FRAP (

). The results demonstrated that all of the studied phytocannabinoids are good antioxidants; however, their efficacy differs depending on the experimental test and the structure of the molecule. Most phytocannabinoids have been shown to have increased activity when tested using SET (single electron transfer) mechanism-based methods, such as ABTS, CUPRAC, and FRAP, but reduced activity when tested using methods based on the HAT (hydrogen atom transfer) and RAF (radical adduct formation) mechanisms, such as DPPH and beta-carotene.

Despite the therapeutic value of phytocannabinoids and their antiradical potential, relatively few investigations on their mechanisms of action have been conducted. In two studies we recently published, we used DFT calculations to describe in detail the scavenging effects of cannabidiol (CBD) and cannabidiolic acid (CBDA) (

; 

). We have shown that these compounds are effective in scavenging hydroperoxyl radicals in polar physiological media but less effective in lipid media. As part of our ongoing research on the antiradical activity of phytocannabinoids, we have evaluated in this paper the antiradical capacity and mechanism of eight compounds that constitute the main families of phytocannabinoids, including cannabinol (CBD), tetrahydrocannabinol (TCBN), cannabichromene (CBC), cannabicyclol (CBL), cannabielsoin (CBE), cannabinodiol (CBND), cannabifuran (CBF), and cannabigerol (CBG) (
Fig. 1
). First, the activity was evaluated against the hydroperoxyl radical, which is a typical radical widely used as a model for the evaluation of the antioxidant activity. Then, based on the findings, the activity of the most promising phytocannabinoid was assessed in physiological aqueous medium against a variety of common radical species.

