The results are reported in Table 1 , and the localized transition states are shown in Fig. 5 . In the lipid-like environment, the radical scavenging capacity of phytocannabinoids is moderate to good with overall rate coefficients of 6.00 × 10 1 to 8.80 × 10 3 M 1 s 1 . The best candidates were found to be, in order, TCBN, CBG, CBF, and CBC. Their overall rate constants are somewhat close to that of BHT (1.70 × 10 4 M 1 s 1 ) (
) suggesting that these molecules are good antioxidants under lipid physiological conditions. Analysis of the branching ratios reveals that the CH group of TCBN plays a significant role in the overall reactivity of the molecule with a contribution of 35% to the overall rate constant. This highlights the potential role of benzylic CH groups in antioxidant action. Similar outcomes were also attained in our earlier work on CBDA (
).

On the other hand, the antiradical activity of phytocannabinoids under physiological polar conditions appears to be substantially better with overall rate coefficients ranging from 5.20 × 104 to 5.25 × 106 M 1 s 1 . CBN, CBC, and CBF are the most promising molecules with rate coefficients of the order of 106 M 1 s 1 . The SET mechanism from the anionic states is dominant or almost exclusive for all phytocannabinoids. This finding is consistent with our earlier works on CBD and CBDA (
;
), as well as experimental investigations on phytocannabinoids (
). In comparison, the calculated rate constants of CBN, CBC, and CBF are larger than that of Trolox (1.30 × 105 M 1 s 1 ) (
) and BHT (2.51 × 10 5 M 1 s 1 ) (
), implying that these phytocannabinoids are effective free radical scavengers under physiologically polar conditions.

Although the reaction toward HOO • is used as a standard, there is some variation in the radical scavenging reactions with other species. Thus, the antiradical activity of the most promising phytocannabinoid in the aqueous medium (CBF) was also examined against a variety of typical free radicals including peroxyl radicals ( CH 3 COO • and Cl 3 COO • ), hydroxyl radical (HO • ), alkoxy radicals ( CH 3 O • and Cl 3 CO • ), nitrogen dioxide (NO 2 ), nitric oxide (NO), superoxide anion (O 2 • – ), sulfate radical anion (SO 4 • – ), and nitride radical (N • 3 ). This study focused exclusively on the SET mechanism from the anionic form of CBF which is the primary mechanism in water at physiological pH. The obtained rate constants are reported in Table 2 . By analyzing the data in Table 2 , we can conclude that CBF has a moderate inhibition capacity against SO 4 • - ( k f = 1.09 × 103 M 1 s 1 ), but an excellent ability to inhibit CH 3 COO • ( k f = 1.88 × 10 6 M 1 s 1 ) and Cl 3 COO • ( k f = 1.88 × 10 6 M 1 s 1 ) as well as CH 3 O • ( k f = 9.11 × 106 M 1 s 1 ) and NO 2 ( k f = 4.26 × 106 M 1 s 1 ). However, CBF is ineffective for scavenging HO • , NO, and O 2 • - under the conditions examined. The prediction of low activity against HO • implies that SET is not the correct mechanism for this radical; highly reactive radicals are known to follow other routes (fHAT or RAF) that are mainly barrierless in aqueous conditions (
;
). These findings corroborate the work of
, which shows that phytocannabinoid antioxidant activity exceeds that of Trolox when radicals/metal ions are reduced through the SET mechanism by the transfer of electrons from phenolic groups.

All density functional theory (DFT) computations in this investigation were performed using the Gaussian 09 program (M. J. 

). All computations were performed using the M062X functional in conjunction with the 6–311++ G (d,p) basis set (

). Previous studies (

; 

) have proven the accuracy of this methodology for free radical reactions. The ground and transition states were confirmed by the number of imaginary frequencies (0 and 1, respectively). The solvation effects of water and pentyl ethanoate were simulated using the SMD solvation model to mimic polar and lipid physiological environments (

). SMD is frequently used to quantify antioxidant activity with low inaccuracy when compared to experimental data (

; 

; 

, 2021). The thermodynamic characteristics associated with the examined antioxidant pathways were computed, as previously described (

, 

; 

). The kinetic calculations were carried out following the QM-ORSA methodology (quantum mechanics-based test for overall free radical scavenging activity) (

, 

). The rate constant (
